Project:¶

https://olympus.greatlearning.in/courses/37429/assignments/138792

Customers’ leaving credit cards services would lead bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers’ and identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and reason for same – so that bank could improve upon those areas

You as a Data scientist at Thera bank need to come up with a classification model that will help bank improve their services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards

Objective¶

Explore and visualize the dataset. Build a classification model to predict if the customer is going to churn or not Optimize the model using appropriate techniques Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the bank

Sections¶

EDA w\ Insights

  • Univariate analysis & Bivariate analysis

Final EDA Insight: Key meaningful observations on the relationship between variables

  • Prepare the data for analysis
    • Missing value Treatment, Outlier Detection(treat, if needed. why or why not ), Feature Engineering, Prepare data for modeling

Model building-Logistic Regression

  • Make a logistic regression model
  • Improve model performance (up/downsampling)
  • Regularize above models, if required

Model building-Bagging and Boosting

  • Build Decision tree, random forest, bagging classifier models
  • Build Xgboost, AdaBoost, and gradient boosting models

Hyperparameter tuning using grid search: GridSearchCV()

  • Tune the best 3 models using grid search and provide the reason behind choosing those models
  • Use pipelines in hyperparameter tuning

Hyperparameter tuning using random searchL: RandomizedSearchCV()

  • Tune the best 3 models using random search and provide the reason behind choosing those models
  • Use pipelines in hyperparameter tuning

Model Performances

  • Compare the model performance of all the models
  • Comment on the time taken by the grid and randomized search in optimization

Business recommendations and insights

Basic Data Scoping

  • Data Dictionary was not accurate about Attrition_Flag.
  • Avg_Utilization_Ratio has a median of .176 which has a large 10 point gap with the mean at around .2748
  • Total Amount Count&Change Q4 to Q1 have a relatively simlar similar mean, standard deviations median and outliers at the 75th percentile & max. These may be highly correlated.
  • Months Inactive has a median of 2 and a mean od 2.34 confirming that statement that many have left recently. Many were on the books for about 36 months per the median of Months on book.
  • Most clients had a revolving balance with extreme spread from a mean of about 360 in the 25th percentile to about 1,800 in the 75th percentile which is only about 500 from the median and a max of 2,500
  • Most customers have 2 children with a few outliers ranging from 3 to 6 children.

  • Age was centerted around 46 with a standard deviation of about 9 years. The age is spread from 26-73 so about 50 years range.

    The following continous int64 values are more catigorical than continous.

  • Dependent_count
  • Total_Relationship_Count
  • Contacts_Count_12_mon
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon

def myHB(feature):
    '''NUMERICAL/CONTINOUS plots -- histogram & boxplot'''
    mypalette = 'Set2'
    sns.set(rc={"figure.figsize": (20, 5)})
    
    sns.displot(data=feature
        ,x=None
        ,y=None
        ,hue=None
        ,row=None
        ,col=None
        ,weights=None
        ,kind='hist'
        ,rug=True
        ,kde=True
        ,palette=mypalette
        ,color=None
    )
    plt.show()
    
    sns.boxplot(data=feature
        ,x=None
        ,y=None
        ,hue=None
        ,orient='h'
        ,color=None
        ,palette=mypalette
        ,linewidth=None
        ,whis=1.5
    )
    plt.show()
    #END OF FUNCTION

def myBar(feature):
    '''DISCRETE/CATEGORICAL plots -- countplot w\ percent'''
    mypalette = 'Set2'
    sns.set(rc={"figure.figsize": (7, 5)})
    ax = sns.countplot(feature, palette=mypalette, order = feature.value_counts().index)   
    ax.xaxis.set_label_position('top') 
    ax.xaxis.tick_top()
    for i in ax.patches:
        # x=plot width & y=plot hieght
        width_x  =((i.get_x() + i.get_width()/2) - (0.04*feature.nunique())) 
        height_y =(i.get_y() + i.get_height()/2)
        
        percentage = "{:.2f}%".format(100 * i.get_height() / len(feature))
        ax.annotate(percentage, (width_x, height_y), size=12)  # annotate the percantage
    if(feature.nunique() > 4):
        plt.xticks(rotation = 45);
    plt.show()  # show the plot

Customer Age

  • Data will be normally distributed after outliers have been taken out.
  • Customer Age is mostly normally distributed. Both tails seem to have a few spikes towards tails but are about even.
  • Age box plot confirms outliers are not too significant.
  • Too early to tell if Customer Age will be a factor.

Gender

  • Customers distribution is mostly comprised of women, however, the feature is balanced.
  • Less than a 5% gap.

Dependent Count

  • Depedent_Count feature favors dependent counts of 2 & 3 most with a slight left skew.
  • The extremes, 0 and 5, are the less frequent.
    • This may indicate most customers are married/cohabitating or divorced couples.

Marital_Status

  • Has several unknown @ 7.4% so this was added to Divorced.
    • The Unknowns are likely to be Divorced or Single people.
    • To determine a good fit: A possible alternative approach for could have been based on ‘Dependent’ count.
  • Married is the most dominant value for this feature with ‘Single’ following thereafter.

Education_Level

  • Has several unknown @ 15% so this was added to Uneducated.
  • Majority are Graduate is the highest category
  • 'College' accounts for 10% which seems low so likely represents Graduate so has been combined.
  • As expected Post-Graduate & Doctorate are the rarest, taking up only about 5% of each.
    • An alternative approach could have been to review Education Level with Income Category
    • Post-Graduate + Doctorate could have been combined but will leave as is

Income_Category

  • Has several unknown @ 10.98% so it has been combined to less than 40k.
  • Distribution is heavly favor on 'Less than 40K' at about 35% which suggests most may have lower education.
    • This is followed respectively by 40K+,60K+, 80K+, 120K+ (in thousands)

Unknowns in categories: Replaced Unknowns got "Uneducated" , "Divorced" & "Less than $40K" as those are social stigma may exist for these these may have been hesitant to report.

Target Value is Attrition_Flag

  • There is a big imbalance, 16% customers have attrited.

Card_Category

  • Most users have the blue category. This accounts for 90%+ of the data in this feature with a small amount trailing behind in silver, then a gold and platnum are almost none existant.
  • May consider grouping Silver, Gold, & Platinum as Premium Cards

Contacts_Count_12_mon No. of Contacts in the last 12 months

  • Contact count is heavily centered around 2 Contacts(33.37%) & 3 Contact(21.86%)

Months_Inactive_12_mon No. of months inactive in the last 12 months

  • Most customer, at least have 1-3 Relationship count, with most 3 & 2, respectively
  • Very few had no countact or more than 3

Total_Relationship_Count Total Transaction Count (Last 12 months)

  • Majority of cutomers had more than 3 Total Relationship counts

def mscore(model, flag=True):
    score_list = []

    pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    pred_test = model.predict(X_test)

    train_acc = model.score(X_train, y_train)
    test_acc = model.score(X_test, y_test)

    train_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_train, pred_train)
    test_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_test, pred_test)

    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_train, pred_train)
    test_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_test, pred_test)

    score_list.extend( ( train_acc, test_acc, train_recall, test_recall, train_precision, test_precision ) )

    # If the flag is set to True then only the following print statements will be dispayed. The default value is set to True.
    if flag == True:
        print("Accuracy on training set : ", model.score(X_train, y_train)*100)
        print("Accuracy on test set : ", model.score(X_test, y_test)*100)
        print("Recall on training set : ", metrics.recall_score(y_train, pred_train)*100)
        print("Recall on test set : ", metrics.recall_score(y_test, pred_test)*100)
        print("Precision on training set : ", metrics.precision_score(y_train, pred_train)*100)
        print("Precision on test set : ", metrics.precision_score(y_test, pred_test)*100)

    return score_list  # returning the list with train and test scores


def cm(model,y_actual , labels = [1, 0]):
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predict)
    cmDF = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=[['Actual 0 - No','Actual 1 - Yes']], columns = [["Predict 0 - No", "Predict 1 - Yes"]])
    
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(i) for i in cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(i) for i in cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)

    plt.figure(figsize = (7,3))
    sns.heatmap(cmDF, annot = labels, fmt='', cmap='Blues', annot_kws={"size":15})
    
    # Individual Elements
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predict).ravel()
    print()
    print('True-Positive: ', tp)
    print('True-Negative: ', tn)
    print('False-Positive: ', fp)
    print('False-Negative: ', fn)

def compareM (comparemodels):
    acc_train = []
    acc_test = []
    recall_train = []
    recall_test = []
    precision_train = []
    precision_test = []

    for model in comparemodels:
        scores = mscore(model, False)
        acc_train.append(scores[0]*100)
        acc_test.append(scores[1]*100)
        recall_train.append(scores[2]*100)
        recall_test.append(scores[3]*100)
        precision_train.append(scores[4]*100)
        precision_test.append(scores[5]*100)
    return acc_test ,acc_train ,precision_test ,precision_train ,recall_test ,recall_train


def importantFeatures(model, show):
    importanceDF = pd.DataFrame(model.feature_importances_, columns = ["Importance"], index = X_train.columns).sort_values(by = 'Importance', ascending = False)
    if (show == True):
        #Boiler plate code

        importances = model.feature_importances_
        indices = np.argsort(importances)
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,12))
        plt.title('Feature Importances')

        plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [feature_names[i] for i in indices])
        plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')

Insight into Choosing the best model

  • As false-negatives are less of a concern. Precision for the situation as we would like there is no penalty/consequence of an attrition client. While undesirable, there is no direct loss.

  • Highest by Test_Accuracy was: XGBoost, RandomForest, GradientBoost

  • Highest by Test_Precision was: XGBoost, GradientBoost, RandomForest

Resulting XGBoost, RandomForest , GradientBoost as our top three to build the pipe build.

for name, model in models:
    kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
    cv_result = cross_val_score(estimator=model, X=X_train_over, y=y_train_over, scoring="precision", cv=kfold)
    results.append(cv_result)
    names.append(name)
    print("{}: {}".format(name, cv_result.mean() * 100))
print()

# Cookie Cutter - boxplot for CV scores of all models defined above
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))

fig.suptitle("Model Performance without Hyperparams")
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)

plt.boxplot(results)
ax.set_xticklabels(names)

plt.show()

  • Out of all the models XGBoost without RandomSearchCV had the best performance.

  • While Test Test_Precision increased, accuracy dropped substatially, by about 12 points with a cv of 3 and 25 iterations.

  • Perhaps raising this would yield better values but due to harward limitations, this could not be tested.

  • Grid Search never completed for any of the models after waiting 4 hours so it will be excluded from this comparison.

  • This leads us to conclude that Random Search is a much faster method for Hypertuning

  • As for the features most important features, they are as follows, however no single one was extraordinarly impactful:

    • Total_Trans_Ct, Total_Relationship_Count, Gender_1,IncomeCategory 40𝐾− 60K, Total_Revolving_Bal

Business Recommendations¶

In the effots to curb Customers’ leaving credit cards services leading to future financial opportunity loss, The bank should focus on customer behavior features Total_Trans_Ct, Total_Relationship_Count, and Total_Revolving_Bal.

Men (Gender_1) that have an Income Category of 40𝐾− 60K(IncomeCategory 40𝐾− 60K) are the customer classification/profile to focus on as these are the highest ones of impact.

Using these features, I would recommend to possibly offer some kind of promotion to them or reach out to them for more personalized service. Perhaps collecting additional data for further analysis would be of benefit.
